At PipeCandy (yes, if you don't realize, we are marketing to you now!), we track DNVBs, D2Cs, Ugly ducklings and what not. Click https:// pipecandy.com (and don't bounce off immediately, ok?) because that's why we wrote this thread :).

Private labels are a trade arbitrage play for retailers (fancy way of saying that it makes them more money). Often, they are commodities where the branding doesn't matter. Hence, they don't brand and hence, they are not a D2C 'brand'. Capiche?

If you see a private label on the aisle and other known brands, how many times would you pick a private label because you remember their TVC or Instagram ad or because you love what they stand for? Not once, right? (Maybe, a few times because you know their price is low). pic.twitter.com/RW8uHdiL1T

What about private labels of retailers? They are brands too and they sell directly to consumers, right? No, but they are not brands in the sense that the retailers aren't really trying to give the brand an identity beyond convenience and pricing. Stay with us. We'll explain.
The only difference between them and the DNVBs is that they have not raised a ton of money yet or have influencers pouting on @instagram with their products. Some of them will eventually get there.

Who are we to say? They seem to have direct customer relationships. We'd invite them to the D2C party. What about the 10s of 1000s (yes there are - check our website!) of eCommerce companies that sell their own brands? They are the ugly cousins to DNVBs.

Indeed. So then can we call @amway and other direct sales companies as 'direct to consumer'? Every pig likes a new lipstick! Some argue that D2C really means one brand (or 'monobrand' if you like coolth) and if a brand manufacturer has a multi-brand strategy they can't be D2C. pic.twitter.com/wQtQEF2e1g
Because talking to shoppers directly helps you serve them better and build new products that are based on real shopper feedback. It also makes more monies! Attractive, right?

All clear so far? Now, @Nike wants to call itself a D2C brand, because 'why not?'. They are setting up their own stores for a long time now and D2C is a channel for them, just like their website. Traditional brands are setting up their own stores and eCommerce stores. Why?
Pop-ups are so popular that services like @appearhere & @b8ta are getting funded to help the brands reach their customers in the physical world, without having a store.

D2C is about ferocious attention to brand building, direct customer conversations and owning that experience wherever the customer is. Brands that cannot set up their own stores go and put out 'pop-up stores'. @nikkibaird of @Aptos_Retail calls it 'uberization' of retail.

Digital sucks when you try to scale. There are only so many impressions you can buy even if you have the monies. So physical retail comes back to the equation. DNVBs start with digital (hence 'native') and move to set up their own stores (Hello, Warby Parker!).

@dunn who created this abbreviation comes from the equity analysis and consulting world. We forgive him because he later gave us @Bonobos . DNVBs are a good way to emphasize that brands are going directly to where customers are & are circumventing retailers. But...

Heard of @Allbirds @Casper @WarbyParker etc.? They are the happening D2C brands. They are 'so happening' that they needed a badge to wear. Some started calling them 'DNVBs' (Digitally Native Vertical Brands). Sounds like 'Collateralized Debt Obligations'? You're not alone :). pic.twitter.com/toW0a76PdL

As the name implies, brands that establish a direct relationship with the customer through trade channels are considered to be 'D2C'. But, there are grey areas and then there are definitions that have gained traction and yet don't do full justice to the trend. Let's explore. pic.twitter.com/vgG9pIjepc
What is a 'direct to consumer' brand? A #thread on the hot & happening #d2c segment.

The notion that retail is dead is dead for a couple of years now. Digital and Silicon Valley echo chambers continue to hold this notion even in the presence of compelling data.

We picked up our crystal ball and looked into 2019 to predict how the Retail and eCommerce industry would fare in 2019. Here's the Forbes article was written by Ashwin Ramasamy. #PredictionsFor2019 #eCommerce #Retail https://www. forbes.com/sites/forbeste chcouncil/2018/11/28/ten-tech-based-predictions-for-the-retail-industry-in-2019/ …

Apparel is a war that’s very much on and Amazon is not going to be the default winner.
These brands create a positioning and an influencer network on Insta that’s simply not possible on Amazon.

D2C luxury and affordable luxury brands are getting launched on Instagram first and much later (if at all) elsewhere. They are the modern day’s alternative to the Uber-luxury brands from France and Italy. They all are on Instagram
Inspite or Amazon being the #1 apparel retailer in the world and the likes of @Nike joining the platform, not all brands like being sold next to a diaper.
Consider the hold Instagram has over global shoppers. It’s not 83% better reach than Amazon in the US. It’s just shy of 10x in the global markets. The dominance will stay. Read why.
Amazon’s online sales revenue from the US accounts for nearly 70% of its total online sales revenue, whereas for Instagram the 105M MAU accounts only for 20% of global MAU.

But that’s 83% more shoppers on Instagram than on Amazon (yes I am making an assumption that all of Instagram shoppers will be buying fashion/lifestyle products and that’s not a stretch). There is more.
Remember, in the US, they had 105M MAU in 2017 & that 72% bought a product they saw on Instagram. Maybe, they bought it from Amazon too.
At about 10 purchased a year, we are talking about 40M shoppers in the US buying apparel from Amazon every year. Let’s compare this with Instagram.
At an average order value of $49, Amazon would have shipped 400M clothing orders last year.

Not all 126M buy apparel. $19B of Amazon’s $177B revenue in 2017 came from apparel. They will be bigger than @Macys already this year. Amazon is the #1 apparel retailer in the US. What does it translate to, in terms of shopper numbers?

Amazon sold to 126M shopper in the US as of 2017. Instagram has about 105M Monthly active users. About 73M of them bought a product they saw on Insta. Seems like a distant follower behind Amazon, right?
It’s likely that Amazon is already the largest apparel retailer in the US. So does Insta still matter as much? It does.
Last year at the @shoporg event of @NRFnews I was at a panel moderated by @mckinsey ’s Ken Fenyo. I had mentioned that @instagram matters more to fashion brands than @amazon .

The store aisles are going to be more fun in 2019. Thanks to powerful mobile phones, AR is no longer tacky. Product experience at the aisles can now be more immersive than ever.
Subscription box companies may continue to struggle in general with churn (except when they are a part of a retailer or a brand loyalty program).

'Click to collect' will become more popular because free+2-day shipping bleeds retailers. Customer convience is an issue but it's not a new habit to form but an old habit to resurrect. US has always been a 'to-go' country.

When social platforms launch ecommerce payments ( @whatsapp , @instagram , @pinduoduo ), the expansion of eCommerce will come from these apps and not from new merchants that Shopify traditionally attracts. Shopify doesn't have its own shoppers and that's a weakness.

Mid-market eCommerce companies have to go cross-border or stay mid-market for ever. Amazon has made it easy for top sellers to go international. When brand loyalties are fickle and marketplace habits are hard to break, indie ecommece companies have to go international decisively.

@instagram will give a run for the money to platforms like @amazon and @Google when it comes to product discovery (in fashion). MAUs are comparable or better for Instagram with high representation of fashion shoppers. When payments happen on @instagram the scale will be tipped.

D2C will still be a big deal but CPGs will be less worried than ever. It's easy to launch a D2C brand (hello, minimalistic ads!) but CAC is hard to reign in. Momentum plays like @allbirds have to prove revenue upside more clearly than earlier cohorts of D2Cs to get strategics in

Computer vision will move to less exciting parts of retail. Product tagging usecases ( @vue_ai ), quality control/returns management for grocery, better planograming ( @TraxRetail ) are already proving that computer vision is ready for retail primetime.

In 2018, @stitchfix , @KidboxOfficial etc. have proven the AI value in creating receipes that keep consumers happy and coming back. This is proof of AI delivering both topline and bottomline. AI is officially mainstream in retail.

Voice shopping will come to your cars. At least, @wholefoods will make it happen for its customers. Car+Alexa+ @amazon + @WholeFoods isn't that hard to guess. Grocery chains will adapt more than the apparel chains (obviously).
Some of the things we think would happen in the eCommerce industry in 2019 (we track half a million eCommerce companies. The predictions are mostly based on our own data)
